text: I like the idea and the Krampus lore, but it looks poorly executed. I'm fucking tired of these shit horror movies that aren't even scary. And horror movies are all about the monster and the characters. When the characters are unlikable like this bunch, I'd rather see everyone die than get out alive. And the setup, how obvious could you get. I'll probably laugh more than feel fear. I also suspect a very slow and boring setup before it actually get interesting about 30 mins in. And of course there's a fucking grandma who knows who Krampus is to fill in the audience. How about you show us who Krampus is through his actions rather than explaining his fucking life story? The element of mystery is a magical thing that this movie could have capitalized on well. I haven't even seen this movie yet and I know it sucks. Dammit, why?

text: Krampus is a for real thing: a figure of German folklore. That makes this all way more interesting, for some reason. The way it goes is this: if a child has been good, she gets gifts from good ol' Saint Nicholas. But if a child has been _bad..._ Santa's buddy Krampus (yes, in some variations Krampus is actually a *crony* of St. Nick's) comes to the child's house instead. And promptly drags the poor kid right to Hell. Maybe a _bit_ extreme, but there it is. Heck, you might want to consider yourself LUCKY if you're some rotten-ass kid and *all that happens* to you on Christmas is a facsimile of Satan delivers you kicking and screaming to the black gates of The Inferno. 'Cause in SOME versions, Krampus has a buddy named Perchta. Or, if you prefer, "The Belly-Slitter". 'Cause... Perchta cuts stomachs. So, disemboweled, _THEN_ tossed to the pits of the christian underworld. Let's hope this movie's _FULLA_ THAT GOOD STUFF, eh?

text: The problem with modern horror movies is that they're mostly made by people who are not intelligent and creative enough to come up with ideas that would really scare people. All they use are cheap lame jump scares. When was the last time you were scared watching a horror movie WITHOUT the scene going something like this:  1) dark room,  2) silence,  3) character walking slowly, camera focused on his face,  4) camera turns into POV mode,  5) a loud sudden sound happens and something jump out, or falls down, etc.   NEVER. It always happens like that. And that is the cheapest, most disgustingly terrible way to make horror films.  Even if a pink fluffy bunny jumped out and some childish cute music started playing loudly, you'd be equally scared for that second, because you weren't scared by the scene, or by what is happening in the movie, you were just startled by the loud sudden noise. And people don't seem to understand that, even worse, they seem to like these stupid jump scares which seem like they were filmed by imbeciles for imbeciles to watch.  For once I'd like to watch a new horror movie that made my skin crawl because of the atmosphere, sound, setting, THE SCRIPT,  and just fully rely on cheap jump scares, in fact, I want a horror movie without a single jump scare. A jump scare in a horror movie is like an explosion in an action movie...sometimes it's best to find different ways to excite the audience.

text: Yet another movie I don't need to see since they literally told me the whole goddamn movie in the trailer.  Family Christmas, typical cliche jokes about the food, people get irritated with each other, blizzard hits, family pisses each other off then they get scared and finally come together in some big moment, idiots creep around in an attic while apparently stranded somewhere without heat or food needing to conserve energy, we get 10 cheap jump scares before the Krampus is finally revealed only to be completely disappointing in its CGI-obviousness, grown adults run around screaming at a character that real children are actually taken to see at Christmas in other countries, family fights Krampus ensuring that Hollywood desecrates yet another cultural legend/icon/myth.  Do the people making these not understand that it's _not_ supposed to be a plot summary?  More money for Netflix and Amazon.

text: The best scary movies are ones that surprise you, consider a dialogue scene where nothing is happening, no one would suspect anything to happen, throw a surprise scare in there and that's scary, a jack in the box playing music. GEE, I WONDER WHAT WILL HAPPEN? And this is unrealistic, you show the houses side by side, 20 feet from another, then a snowstorm hits? Ok, go 20 feet to the right!  People say the conjuring was bad, but I liked it. It definitely brought a good demonic film better than any of that paranormal activity bullshit. And with 'The Visit' and 'Krampus' coming up I think the horror franchise is doomed, people hate the good ones but love the cheesy things.    Krampus is a good idea, but I think we need a fresh take on it.

text: As an Austrian who grew up with the "Krampus" tradition, I have to say that the movie does not reflect this character at all.  1. Krampus is coming on 5 or 6 of december (depending on the region in Austria/Germany) - but NOT on Christmas 2. He has no little "helpers" 3. Krampus is here to punish bad kids and take them with him, so adults dont have to fear him 4. Bad kids also get a piece of coal as present from Krampus  I recommend taking a look at several "Perchtenlauf" videos on YouTube.

text: I remember, in primary school our vice principal used to dress as Santa and visited the classes with small children. When we got older, we dressed as a krampusz (mask with horns and furcoat), we stood next to Santa and our job was to scare the children and say that we will take them away if they're naughty. I come from Hungary, and I think who grew up knowing that Santas helpers are the kramuszes and not cute little elves, this feels like if it would say: Beware... THE BOOGIEMAN! My first reaction was laughter but it turned out to be grotesk and very creepy because it brings back my deep childhood fears. I mean it's different to face the demon you knew than to meet a new one right?

text: This film looks fun for some level of dark comedy camp value. Definate Gremlins vibe. That being said, Krampus has obviously become a "thing" here in America. Something we have jacked from another culture to fit our own designs, like what we've done with Day of the Dead. We take it, debase it, sensationalize it, or water it down to where its unrecognizable from its origins. Dont get me wrong, this film looks like campy fun, but it's seriously a sign of the times.

text: I'll be the one to drop the explanation for the ignorant: in certain parts of Europe they celebrate the Christmas season with the story of Saint Nicholas, rather than Santa Claus, though they are very similar.  Saint Nicholas is, as his name implies, a saint of the Church who goes around during the yule season and rewards good boys and girls with presents.  But in certain regions, they believe that Saint Nicholas has a counterpart named Krampus. He's an ugly monster who punishes bad children by spanking them with birch tree branches and tossing them in a giant sack and carrying them away.  Krampus night is observed in some countries on the night of December 5th with festivals and parades where adults dress in monster costumes and scare the little kiddies.  And now, the big guy finally gets the Hollywood treatment-should have come well before The Gingerdead Man or Jack Frost.

I don't love horror as a genre (come on, this is horror at its core, calling it horror-comedy is just a means of trying to make it seem a bit less dark so it's more marketable), but the thing that first grabbed me about this was the knowledge that Krampus was from real folklore - I knew the name because of Don't Starve, and in the trivia there had been some description of the myth he was based on, so I already kind of knew when I saw the trailer in theaters. The promise of this movie, of course, made me research the myth a lot more, and WOW, is it an interesting legend! Once upon a time, Christmas wasn't just a commercialized day of happiness and colors and lights, it /meant/ something. The fact that St. Nicholas was accompanied by a demon who whipped the kids who'd been bad while the saint himself gave gifts to the kids that were good gives the whole "naughty or nice" thing SO much more meaning - better than just "you don't get presents", it's "you get punished". I LOVE it. Maybe, just maybe, this movie will finally start to bring down America's over-commercialized milking of the holiday. I mean, probably not, America's probably beyond helping, but hey, a girl can dream. XD

text: OMG, as if getting coal for Christmas wasn't bad enough!  Now people get death?!  =0 At 1:22, the creepy old lady character they stereotypically throw into these kind of movies for exposition says "Instead, a much darker, ancient spirit" and then at 2:00 says "He is the shadow of Saint Nicholas" as if darkness and shadows are scary, evil, or unnatural.  But there's no need to be afraid of the dark or of our shadow, and they are not a negative or unnatural things.  It's kind of odd how some people feel about darkness.  When talking about certain things, some people equate the dark to being scary, bad, or evil, but I never could understand it.  =/ This is just a philosophical thought, but if darkness has been around ever since the beginning of everything before anything else, is all around us, and there is even inside of us (I imagine it gets pretty dark inside of our bodies.  I don't think we have light bulbs inside of us), and follows us around in the form of our shadow, isn't darkness one of the most natural and non-evil things out there?  =o And night time is actually one of the most peaceful times for most people.  It's when we rewind, recharge, and heal.  Can't people just say what they mean? Could have easily said "evil" there, you know. l=/ And I've heard some things about this Krampus.  I've heard he punishes the bad.  So, does that, in a way, make him good?  He's like a supernatural Punisher or something.  l=D

text: The Story: Krampus "kills" most of the family until only half or a few remain. A selfless act from the "survivors" at the climax will reveal Krampus' true intentions, which are to teach the family to work together and quit being so selfish. Krampus is good for caring about peoples moral compass while Santa will be revealed as the true evil for making people selfish and materialistic in their youth. The family will live on happily and humbly, teaching the audience a lesson in humility and caring for one another. Unfortunately this is all being done to make Baphomet (and ultimately Satan) viewed as a likable and caring entity capable of uniting people with love. Open your eyes and enjoy the show ;)

text: First of all, don't associate Santa with a Krampus, they have NOTHING in common. I'm from Slovenia and our Krampus is called "Parkelj", while his companion, St. Nicholas, is called "Miklav≈æ". Krampus suppose to punish and scare kids who were bad through the year, while St. Nicholas rewards them.   I remember times when my father (or my neighbour) was scaring us on 5th of December and we needed to pray in order for them to stop/go away. They were doing it with voices and chains around the house and it was scary for a kid. Of course at some point I realised it's not real and that my father is always suspiciously disappearing before the noises start. :) The next day a basket of goods were waiting for us (commonly oranges, chocolate St. Nicholas, figs, etc.), which was left by St. Nicholas‚Äìmy mother, of course.

text: There haven't been very many good horror movies lately. They all seem very samey to me, so I always love when something creative comes out. Saw this movie in theatres and overall, I can describe it as "fun." It's just fun to watch. The monster designs are really cool, Krampus himself is cool, and the whole idea of a twisted Christmas horror is refreshing. It also has quite a bit of comedy and doesn't take itself seriously AT ALL, trust me. It isn't a theatre movie, though. I recommend seeing it when it comes out on Blu-Ray/Netflix/etc with a few friends. It's one of those kind of movies. Overall, I liked it a lot more than I thought I would.

text: I saw this movie two days ago...in an empty theater. Seriously, I was the only person in the room. And before I'd gone to see it, I asked my mother to tell me a thing or two about the character of Krampus, since she lived in Germany when she was a child. The movie begins just a few days before Christmas, which is unusual, because Krampusnacht (Krampus Night) is set on the evening of December 5th. And one character stated Krampus is thousands of years old, but my research  said his type of folklore have only been around for a few hundred years, which is very old, but doesn't technically classify him as being "ancient". Perhaps my research wasn't perfect, or maybe the movie twisted a few elements of the character's existence around to add a creepier tone to the story.

text: I saw it and I honestly thought it was perfect, 10/10. it had the three h's of horror; humor, heart, horror. if you didn't like it then horror comedy isn't your forte. Don't bitch about how it wasn't scary, I found it very creepy and humorous at the same time. Not every horror movie needs to be scary, I swear it's like a majority of you never heard of horror sub-genres like gothic romance, horror anthology, etc. ugh point is a large portion of you expect a horror movie like silent hill. silent hill over uses blood, gore and complete insanity which I'll admit I love though you get "used to it". Horror movies shouldn't be typical, they should be unique in their own way from a rising build up to it's climax then a complete twist on the resolution. But hey I'm entitled to my opinion so like it matters :p

text: The Grinch, sitting in his chair planning his next naughty deed against Christmas and Santa was startled when he suddenly heard loud stomps from above, then the sound of something moving down his chimney. (Santa?) the Grinch thought, until the growls and rattling chains echoed as the chimney started to creek and crack. Then he saw claws coming through the shadows inside the fireplace, followed by two black horns. He stared in raising horror as the figure before him fully emerged and had risen up, dressed in a torn christmas cloak. *The Shadow of Saint Nick had come, Krampus.*
